Logic operations

For a given vector \(a = (1, 15, 3, 20, 5, 8, 9, 10, 1, 3)\),

library(classdata)
library(ggplot2)

a = c(1, 15, 3, 20, 5, 8, 9, 10, 1, 3)
  1. less than 20
a < 20
##  [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
  1. squared value is at least 100 or less than 10
(a^2 >= 100) | (a^2 < 10)
##  [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE
a^2
##  [1]   1 225   9 400  25  64  81 100   1   9
  1. equals 1 or 3
(a == 1) | (a == 3)
##  [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE
a %in% c(1, 3)
##  [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE
  1. even
a
##  [1]  1 15  3 20  5  8  9 10  1  3
(a %% 2) == 0
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
((a / 2) - floor(a / 2)) == 0
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE

“filter” function

library(tidyverse)

A1 = dplyr::filter(fbi, year == 2014, state == "Iowa")
  1. Get a subset of all crimes in Iowa, Plot incidences/rates for one type of crime over time.
A2 = dplyr::filter(fbi, state == "Iowa")
ggplot(data = A2, aes(x = year, y = count / population)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap(~type, scales = "free_y")

  1. Get a subset of all crimes in 2009. Plot the number or rate for one type of crime by state.
A3 = dplyr::filter(fbi, year == 2009, type %in% c("homicide", "arson", "robbery"))
ggplot(data = A3, aes(x = state)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(weight = count / population)) + coord_flip() + 
  facet_wrap(~type, scale = "free")

  1. Get a subset of the data that includes number of homicides for the last five years. Find the rate of homicides, extract all states that have a rate of greater than 90% of the rates across all states, and plot
A4 = dplyr::filter(fbi, year %in% c(2016 : 2020), type == "homicide")
A4$homicide.rate = A4$count / A4$population * 66000
quan09 = quantile(A4$homicide.rate, 0.9)
A5 = dplyr::filter(A4, homicide.rate > quan09)

ggplot(A5, aes(x = state)) + geom_bar(aes(weight = homicide.rate)) + 
  facet_wrap(~year) + coord_flip()

“replace” function

Replace the problematic value in life expectancy for Canada in 1957 in the gapminder data set by 69.96.

B = read.csv("gapminder-5060.csv")
dplyr::filter(B, country == "Canada", year == 1957)
##   country continent year lifeExp      pop gdpPercap
## 1  Canada  Americas 1957  999999 17010154  12489.95
B$lifeExp = replace(B$lifeExp, (B$country == "Canada") & (B$year == 1957), 69.96)
dplyr::filter(B, country == "Canada", year == 1957)
##   country continent year lifeExp      pop gdpPercap
## 1  Canada  Americas 1957   69.96 17010154  12489.95
